DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.


$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,9,1);
$funct = "\( f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{ x - $a }} \)";


$domain = "($a, infinity)" ;
$range = "(0, infinity)";

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 16:
$BR $SPACE $BR
Let $SPACE $funct ,
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
Find the domain and range algebraically:
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
a) What is the domain of $BITALIC f(x)${EITALIC}? $SPACE \{ ans_rule(25) \} \{ htmlLink(qq!http://math.luc.edu/~spiegler/interval.html!,"click here for help using interval notation") \} 
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
b) What is the range of $BITALIC f(x)${EITALIC}? $SPACE \{ ans_rule(25) \}

END_TEXT

ANS(interval_cmp( $domain ) );
ANS(interval_cmp( $range ) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR
$BBOLD SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR
a) To evaluate \( f(x) \) we must have \( x - $a > 0 \).  Thus the domain is \( x > $a \) or in interval notation \( ( $a , + \infty ) \).
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) To find the range, we want to know all of the possible output values.  We solve the equation \( y = f(x) \) for \( x \) in terms of \( y \).  Since
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( y = \frac{1}{\sqrt{ x - $a}} \)
$BR
Squaring both sides gives,
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( y^2 = \frac{1}{x-$a} \)
$BR
Multiplying by \( x - $a \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( y^2 ( x - $a ) = 1 \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( y^2 x - $a y^2 = 1 \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( y^2 x = 1 + $a y^2 \)
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( x = \frac{ 1 + $a y^2}{y^2} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
This formula tells us how to find the $BITALIC x${EITALIC}-value which corresponds to a given $BITALIC y${EITALIC}-value.  The formula works for any $BITALIC y $EITALIC except \( y = 0 \).  We know that \( y \) must also be positive, since \( \sqrt{ x - $a } \) is positive (evaluating a square root always gives a non-negative number).  Therefore it follows that the range is
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( y > 0 \ \ \mbox{or equivalently} \ \ ( 0 , + \infty ) \)
$BR 
END_SOLUTION
      
